[Event "Baker Bridge - Roman Key Card Blackwood"]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "1"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "W:T62.Q2.T532.7643 97.AK96.AQ974.A5 854.J43.J86.T982 AKQJ3.T875.K.KQJ"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "6H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "W"]
pass 1D pass 1S pass 2H pass 4NT pass 5C pass 5D pass 5H pass 6H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 1, chOption: N, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:0, nBasis: 2, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "7a12a763caed335cd1b201e71257a8a11377c2f14e45648d2bf87be57739cafb"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/roman_keycard"]
[Student "S"]
{Your 2\H bid is a Reverse, showing 17+ points.  

There has been no agreement on trumps, so you assume that South has implicitly agreed to \Hs. So you respond 5\C, showing 4 Key-Cards, three Aces and the \HK. Partner next bids 5\D.  

5\D is the Queen Ask. Partner obviously is thinking about a Grand Slam and wants to know whether you hold the trump Queen (\HQ). Since you do not have the card you return to the agreed trump suit at the lowest level - which is 5\H. Partner now bids 6\H.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "W:A63.AK9865.K.A32 QJ52.7.9643.Q864 K7.QJ3.AQJT875.K T984.T42.2.JT975"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "7NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "W"]
1H pass 2D pass 3H pass 4NT pass 5C pass 5NT pass 6D pass 7NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "1179ea27800a993cb2bfe45b4808ea07a1563f441b3b7a6aa517b5dafe8919cb"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/roman_keycard"]
[Student "S"]
{The bidding has been as shown. Yes, you could have jump-shifted on your first bid.  

Slam in \Hs is almost certain, but you should check for Key-Cards. You bid 4NT and partner says 5\C.  

Partner shows 1 or 4 Key-cards. Since he jumped on the second round you figure it must be 4. So you have all the Key-Cards. Time to find out about the other Kings, so you bid 5NT. Partner replies 6\D.  

Partner has 1 King, the only one left, the \DK. You can count about 17 high-card tricks available so you bid 7NT.}

